oto_url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/7/7e/Henry_Richardson_Labouisse%2C_Jr..jpg"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST002"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"achievement","header":"Accepted UNICEF's 1965 Nobel Peace Prize","body":"Henry Labouisse became Executive Director of UNICEF in 1965 — the year UNICEF was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize. He accepted the prize on the organization's behalf. UNICEF would conduct major relief operations under his fourteen-year leadership, including during the Nigerian civil war in 1968 and in Cambodia in 1979."},{"number":2,"category":"marriage","header":"Married Eve Curie; son-in-law of Marie Curie","body":"His second marriage on November 19, 1954 to Ève Curie made him son-in-law of Pierre and Marie Curie. The Curie family won five Nobel Prizes — Pierre and Marie (Physics 1903), Marie again (Chemistry 1911), Irène and Frédéric Joliot-Curie (Chemistry 1935), and Henry himself accepting the Peace Prize for UNICEF in 1965. Ève survived him by twenty years, dying in 2007 at age 102."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Great-great-grandson of Confederate bishop Leonidas Polk","body":"His mother Frances Devereux Huger Labouisse descended from Leonidas Polk (X00867) — the Episcopal bishop killed as a Confederate general at Pine Mountain in 1864. Polk's daughter Elizabeth Devereux Polk married William Elliott Huger; their daughter Frances was Henry's mother. The Curie marriage thus joined Henry's two genealogical headlines — Hooker-Edwards Puritan lineage on the New England side, Polk Confederate aristocracy on the Louisiana side."}],"slug":"henry-labouisse-1904"}},"burialCemetery":null,"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[]}